messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
My wife is in the bathroom. She's bleeding all over the place. She thinks she's having a baby.
Is she having the baby right now?
I think so. I think she's in labor.
Okay, what's your address, sir?
Oh my God, I'm looking at a baby.
Okay, listen, I need your address.
I have a baby. Oh my God.
Okay, hold on. You didn't know she was pregnant?
No, I had no idea my wife was pregnant.
What's the phone number you're at?
That's my cell phone number.
Oh my God. My wife is holding a baby.
How old is she?
27 years old. She's had three children, two of mine, one before me.
Okay, I'm going to tell you what to do. You need to get out of the bathroom.
She's fine. Oh my God, I'm looking at a baby.
Okay, calm down. Is the baby crying or breathing?
Yeah, she's crying.
We need to get a cloth and you need to wipe off the baby's mouth and nose, okay?
Hold on, Carrie. What's, ma'am? Sorry, I didn't hear you, ma'am.
You need to dry the baby off with a dry towel.
Okay, I've got towels.
Don't pull the cord out. Leave it loose.
Okay, put the baby in a towel.
Put the baby in the mother's arms or on her belly.
Okay, it's fine.
Wrap a towel around the baby to keep it warm.
Okay, oh my God. The placenta is out.
Okay, don't push. We're going to work on tying the cord off. Get a piece of string or a shoelace.
Find a piece of string or a shoelace. I don't care what shoe.
Oh my God, how could she pretend she wasn't pregnant?
Try to get her to lay back, we want her to lay down.
Carrie, just get as comfortable as possible. Now one goes on the way.
Tie the cord off about 6 inches from the baby.
Okay, she said tie the cord off about 6 inches from the baby's belly.
How tight? Pretty tight, but don't cut it.
Yep, that's good.
You said the placenta came out already?
Yep, there's nothing connected to my wife.
I want you to get another towel and wrap the placenta in it.
Carrie, wrap the placenta in a towel.
Put the baby on mom's belly. How's mom doing?
She's sore but calm.
Okay, get a blanket to wrap around mom.
Oh my God, is the front light on?
Is she bleeding profusely?
Honey, are you bleeding real bad?
No, she's not.
Okay, it looks normal from the other births.
Yes, it's not like going all over, just a bit.
How's the baby's color?
He's fine. He looks just like me.
Okay, she's not bleeding real bad?
No.
How's the baby looking?
He's perfectly fine. I'm looking right at him.
Okay, just relax. Let her know they are on the way.
They're on the way, honey.
She did a wonderful job.
She did a great job for not knowing she was pregnant.
Can I talk to her?
Here, talk to him for a second.
Hi.
What's your name?
Tyler Whitney.
So now you're a big brother?
Yep, I have one brother. Now I have two and two sisters.
Cool. What's dad's name?
Dan and Ryan.
Is Ryan the one there tonight?
Yes.
What's mom's name?
Carrie.
How exciting to have a new baby!
Really exciting.
How old are you?
How's mom doing?
She's laying on the floor with the baby.
Okay, can you give the phone back to mom?
Okay.
Hello.
Hi. So what's going on with the baby? Is he dirty?
Yes, he has meconium on his head.
That's normal. Babies are usually cleaned up by the hospital.
Okay.
Is the baby breathing?
Yes, he's blowing bubbles. What a surprise.
How are you feeling?
A little sore, but pretty good.
Your son Tyler is very excited about the new baby.
Oh, they just said they're here.
Congratulations!
Thank you.
